6 "§ 116B-6. Administration of Escheat Fund; Escheat Account.
7 (a) Escheat Account. – All funds received by the Treasurer as escheated or abandoned
8 property and which were transferred prior to January 1, 1980, to the trust fund created under
9 G.S. 116-209 shall remain in that trust fund and shall be placed in a special fund, designated the
10 "Escheat Account."The Escheat Account is established as a special fund in the Reserve Trust
11 Fund created under G.S. 116-209.
12 (b) Investment and Transfer of Assets; Income. – The Treasurer is the trustee of the
13 Escheat Account and has full power to invest and reinvest the assets of the Escheat Account and
14 the Escheat Fund. Subject to the Treasurer's withholding an amount necessary to accomplish the
15 Treasurer's duties as set out in this Chapter, including subsections (e), (f) (f), and (g) of this
16 section, the Treasurer shall transfer, at least annually, to the Escheat Account all moneys then in
17 the Treasurer's custody received as, or derived from the disposition of, escheated and abandoned
18 property and shall disburse to the State Education Assistance Authority, as provided in
19 G.S. 116B-7, the income derived from the investment of the Escheat Account and the Escheat
20 Fund. All moneys transferred to the Escheat Account under this section shall be accounted for
21 and administered separately from other assets and money in the trust fund Reserve Trust Fund
22 created under G.S. 116-209.
23 (c) Security Interest in Escheat Account. – The State Education Assistance Authority, in
24 addition to other powers vested under G.S. 116-201 to G.S. 116-209.23, inclusive, is authorized
25 to Article 23 of Chapter 116 of the General Statutes, may pledge and or vest a security interest
26 in all or any part of the Escheat Account, by resolution adopted or trust agreement approved by
27 it, as security for or insurance respecting the payment of bonds or other obligations, as defined
28 in G.S. 116-201, including principal, interest interest, and redemption premium, if any; provided,
29 that such premium. A pledge and of or security interest in the Escheat Account shall, in the
30 determination of the Authority, constitute a use of the Escheat Fund to aid worthy and needy
31 students who are residents of this State and are enrolled in public institutions of higher education
32 in this State. The Authority may submit to the Treasurer, from time to time as it deems necessary,
33 Treasurer requisitions for transfers of money in the Escheat Account to pay such bonds and other
34 obligations to the extent necessary under such the pledge of, or security interest in, the Escheat
35 Account, or any part thereof, and the Treasurer is authorized and directed to shall pay such money
36 so requisitioned this money to the Authority for such these purposes.
37 (d) Limitation on Amount of Obligations Secured. – The principal amount of bonds and
38 other obligations insured or secured by the Escheat Account shall not exceed 10 times the amount
39 held for the credit of the Escheat Account, as certified from time to time by the Treasurer, and,
40 in no event, shall exceed three hundred fifty million dollars ($350,000,000). If the amount held
41 for the credit of the Escheat Account, as certified by the Treasurer, shall be is ten percent (10%)
42 or less of the principal amount of the bonds and other obligations so insured or secured, the
43 Authority shall not issue any additional bonds or cause additional obligations to be insured or
44 secured by the Escheat Account until such time as the amount held for the credit of the Escheat
45 Account exceeds ten percent (10%) of the principal amount of the bonds and other obligations
46 secured or insured by the Escheat Account.
47 (e) Use of Excess Funds. – If the amount held for the credit of the Escheat Account at
48 any time shall exceed the sum of exceeds thirty-five million dollars ($35,000,000), such the
49 excess may be used by the State Education Assistance Authority, with the written approval of
50 the Treasurer, for the purpose of either (i) making student loans or (ii) refunding outstanding
51 bonds or other obligations issued by the Authority and secured by a pledge of, or a security
