10 "§ 143-716. Definitions.
11 The following definitions apply in this Article:
12 (1) Commission. – The Tobacco Trust Fund Commission.
13 (2) Compensatory programs. – Programs developed by the Commission to
14 identify, locate, compensate, and indemnify tobacco producers, former
15 allotment holders, and persons engaged in tobacco-related businesses who
16 have suffered actual economic losses in this State due to lost quota, the decline
17 in value of tobacco-related personal property assets, and declining market
18 conditions resulting from the Master Settlement Agreement or declines in the
19 tobacco-related segment of the State's economy.
20 (3) Fund. – The Tobacco Trust Fund.
21 (4) Master Settlement Agreement. – The settlement agreement between certain
22 tobacco manufacturers and the states, as incorporated in the consent decree
23 entered in the action of State of North Carolina v. Philip Morris, Incorporated,
24 et al., 98 CVS 14377, in the General Court of Justice, Superior Court Division,
25 Wake County, North Carolina.
26 (5) National Tobacco Grower Settlement Trust. – The trust established by tobacco
27 companies to provide payments to tobacco growers and allotment holders in
28 14 states for the purposes of ameliorating potential adverse economic
29 consequences of likely reduction in demand, sales, and prices for tobacco as
30 an agricultural product as a result of the Master Settlement Agreement.
31 (6) Qualified agricultural programs. – Programs developed by the Commission to
32 support and foster the vitality and solvency of the tobacco-related segment of
33 the State's agricultural economy, particularly the segment adversely affected
34 by the Master Settlement Agreement, with the objective of alleviating and
35 avoiding unemployment, preserving, preserving and increasing local tax
36 bases, and encouraging the economic stability of participants in the State's
37 agricultural economy. Examples of qualified agricultural programs this term
38 include programs to finance the modernization of farming equipment,
39 programs to finance the conversion of existing equipment to conform to
40 environmental and other regulatory requirements, and programs to finance the
41 conversion or replacement of equipment in order to cultivate crops that are
42 more profitable than are currently being cultivated.cultivated, and programs
43 to establish farmers' markets serving communities where tobacco is or was
44 formerly grown.
45 (7) Tobacco product component business. – An individual, partnership, limited
46 liability company, corporation, or other commercial entity that engages in the
47 manufacture of component products for use in the manufacture of tobacco
48 products.
49 (8) Tobacco-related business. – An individual, partnership, limited liability
50 company, corporation, or other commercial entity that provides products or
51 services used directly in (i) the production of tobacco, tobacco or (ii) support
