12 "§ 143-720. Benefits and administration of Fund for compensatory programs.
13 (a) Funds held in the Fund may be expended on compensatory programs as provided in
14 this section.
15 (b) The Fund may provide direct and indirect financial assistance, in accordance with
16 criteria established by the Commission and to the extent allowed by law, to accomplish the
17 following:
18 (1) Indemnify tobacco producers, former allotment holders, and persons engaged
19 in tobacco-related businesses from the adverse economic effects in this State
20 of the Master Settlement Agreement.
21 (2) Compensate tobacco producers, former allotment holders, and persons
22 engaged in tobacco-related businesses for economic loss resulting from lost
23 quota and compensate tobacco producers for the decline in value of
24 tobacco-related personal property assets and declining market conditions
25 resulting from the Master Settlement Agreement in this State.
26 (3) Compensate individuals displaced from tobacco-related employment in this
27 State as a result of the adverse economic effects of the Master Settlement
28 Agreement.
29 (4) Compensate tobacco product component businesses that are (i) adversely
30 impacted by the Master Settlement Agreement and that (ii) need financial
31 assistance to retool machinery or equipment or to retrain workers, in order to
32 convert to the production of new products or nontobacco use of existing
33 products, or to effect other similar changes.
34 (c) Only tobacco producers, persons engaged in tobacco-related businesses, individuals
35 displaced from tobacco-related employment, and tobacco product component businesses in this
36 State, and former holders of North Carolina tobacco allotments allotments, are eligible to apply
37 for and receive assistance pursuant to subsection (b) of this section. Direct payments made to
38 tobacco producers, tobacco allotment holders, and persons engaged in tobacco-related businesses
39 shall be based on losses resulting in 1998 and thereafter. Lost quota shall be a primary
40 determinative factor in calculating the amount of compensable economic loss for tobacco
41 producers, former allotment holders, and persons engaged in tobacco-related businesses.
42 (d) The Commission shall determine the priority of awards among the categories in
43 subsection (b) of this section and within each of those categories.
44 (e) Financial assistance awards shall be for no more than one year at a time. An award
45 may be renewed annually, without limitation.
46 (f) The Commission may require applicants to provide copies of documents necessary to
47 determine compensable economic loss.
48 (g) In no event shall the amount paid to a tobacco producer or allotment holder pursuant
49 to this Article, when combined with the amount received through the National Tobacco Grower
50 Settlement Trust, exceed the compensable economic loss of the producer or allotment holder.
